{[%evp 0,3,61,25,42,43] Before this round, I was on the '-1' mark, which I was not satisfied with. What's more, in my previous game, I was unlucky enough to make the 'mouseslip' move on the real board, which cost me half a point. Nevertheless, I was highly motivated for this game.} 1. e4 {[%emt 0:00:44]} e6 {[%emt 0:00:35]} 2. d4 {[%emt 0:00:06]} d5 {[%emt 0:00:05]} 3. Nc3 {[%emt 0:00:03]} Bb4 {[%emt 0:00:04] As my opponent mainly prefers the Winawer variation, I had the opportunity to prepare thoroughly for this game.} 4. e5 {[%emt 0:00:14]} Ne7 {[%emt 0:00:08]} 5. a3 {[%emt 0:00:04]} Bxc3+ {[%emt 0:00:04]} 6. bxc3 {[%emt 0:00:04]} c5 {[%emt 0:00:05]} 7. Qg4 {[%emt 0:00:03]} Qc7 {[%emt 0:00:47]} 8. Bd3 {[%emt 0:01:50] [#] Here is an example of how training young players can benefit a coach. This move was suggested to me by my student. When I was young, everyone automatically took on g7.} (8. Qxg7 Rg8 9. Qxh7 cxd4 10. Ne2 Nbc6 {[%csl Re5]} 11. f4) 8... cxd4 {[%emt 0:01:24]} 9. Ne2 {[%emt 0:00:38]} dxc3 {[%emt 0:00:19]} 10. Qxg7 {[%emt 0:00:53]} Rg8 {[%emt 0:00:14]} 11. Qxh7 {[%emt 0:00:40]} Qxe5 {[%emt 0:06:45] Black follows the most popular line.} ({The main point of 8.d3 is that after} 11... Nbc6 {White can defend the e5 pawn with the bishop.} 12. Bf4 {which is much better than playing f2-f4, as it happens in the mainline of 8.xg7.}) 12. Bf4 {[%emt 0:00:37]} Qf6 {[%emt 0:10:35]} 13. h4 {[%emt 0:00:33]} Nbc6 {[%emt 0:04:44] This was a new move for me. My preparation had covered both 13...d7 and 13...xg2.} 14. Bg5 {[%emt 0:03:46]} Qe5 {[%emt 0:02:37]} 15. f4 {[%emt 0:22:42]} Qc7 {[%emt 0:02:25]} ({During the game, my main concern was invading the d2 square, since I wasn't sure what I should do - to pick up the exchange or allow d2. The engine says that White is winning in both cases. However it should not confuse you, as the Winawer variation is just a poor choice against the engine. In practice, everything is trickier.} 15... Qe3 16. f5 (16. Rh3 Qd2+ 17. Kf1 $18) 16... Rxg5 17. hxg5 $18 {Black's main problem is the poor position of his king.}) 16. h5 {[%emt 0:16:57][%cal Gh5h6,Gh7g8]} Bd7 {[%emt 0:05:20] [#]} 17. Qxg8+ $1 {[%emt 0:00:13] This move isn't as good as 17.h6, but this game wouldn't be so interesting without it.} ({The engine says that White can calmly pick up the f7 pawn and escape to h5, but for me it wasn't obvious.} 17. h6 $1 O-O-O 18. Qxf7 Rdf8 19. Qh5 Nf5 {[%csl Re1][%cal Gc6d4,Ge6e5,Gc7b6] with thes ideas of e6-e5 and b6. The black king is safe, the h-pawn will not become the queen in near future, while the white king does not feel so safe.}) 17... Nxg8 {[%emt 0:00:12]} 18. h6 {[%emt 0:00:02] The funny thing about this position is that Stockfish 8 (I still have it on my laptop) and Stockfish 17 evaluate it differently. The older engine does not believe in White's sacrifice and at first says that Black is even slightly better. At the same time, the newer engine thinks White is better.  During the game, I was quite optimistic and thought that objectively White is out of serious risk, however, in a long run, I misevaluated the weakness of the c2 pawn which is White's permanent problem.} f6 {[%emt 0:15:31] To be honest, I didn't see this move and thought that Black should take the pawn.} ({My main line was the following one.} 18... Nxh6 $1 19. Rxh6 Bc8 $8 {I thought Black would have to play this, but the f7-f6 pawn sacrifice, with the idea of opening the 7th rank for the queen, also makes some sense. I wasn't sure how to go about this job. White can play Rh7 or first to check, and then return to h7. I also thought about moving Bf6, which is not the best choice for the engine, but it attacks the c3 pawn and takes control of the long diagonal. In all cases, White has a sufficient compensation because: 1) Ra8 and Bc8 are out of the play for a while; 2) dark-squared control; 3) a weakness of the c3 and f7 pawns; 4) it's not easy to say what Black must plan.} 20. Rh7 $44 {[%cal Gg5f6,Ge1f2,Gf2g3,Ga1h1]}) 19. Bg6+ {[%emt 0:02:43]} ({The engine says that White can get an advantage by winning the exchange.} 19. h7 O-O-O 20. h8=Q fxg5 $13 {[%csl Rf4][%cal Ge6e5,Ge5e4]} 21. fxg5 {but I didn't really get what would happen after} e5 {This is why I decided to trap the opponent's king in the middle.}) 19... Ke7 {[%emt 0:00:21]} 20. h7 {[%emt 0:00:22]} Nh6 {[%emt 0:21:13] My opponent naturally preferred the position with an extra queen as the exchange sacrifice wasn't so good with the king in the center.} (20... fxg5 21. h8=Q gxf4 22. Qg7+ Kd6 23. Rh8 Nce7 24. Bh7 $18 {Black doesn't have many chances to counterattack because of the position of g8.}) 21. Bxh6 {[%emt 0:00:21]} Qb6 {[%emt 0:00:21][%csl Re1][%cal Gc6d4,Gd7b5] Black stopped the pawn, protected his king, and now is starting to counterattack. His ideas are e6-e5 and g4 or d4 to exchange the knight, resulting in weakening the white king's position.} 22. Rd1 $1 {[%emt 0:02:11][%cal Rc6d4] My first defending move is correct; White prevents d4.} e5 $1 {[%emt 0:02:07][%cal Gd7g4] [#] Black opens the h3-c8 diagonal and prepares both d4 and g4.} 23. f5 $2 {[%emt 0:23:00][%csl Ge3,Rh6][%cal Rd7g4,Gh6c1] Even though I trapped my bishop on g6, I was happy to find this move because it stops both g4 and d4. However, there was a third move for Black.} (23. Rh4 $5 {This was my favourite for most of my long thinking, but finally I rejected it. The conclusion was right: 23.h4 was not the best move, but the reasoning behind it wasn't very good.} Nd4 $2 ({Here is what I missed.} 23... exf4 $1 $13 {Black wants to play e5, which will give him a good position.}) {At least, I was right about evaluating the capture.} 24. Nxd4 $4 (24. fxe5 $3 {Unfortunately, I didn't think of this.} Nxe2 25. Kxe2 fxe5 {The black queen attacks g6 but White has an important check with a winning position.} 26. Bg5+ $1 Kd6 27. Bd3 $16 {Despite engine's "+1.2" the position remains complicated.}) 24... exd4 $19 {e6 and b5 secures Black a winning position.} 25. Bg7 Bb5 {[%cal Gb6e6,Ge6e2,Gd4d3]}) ({At first, I wanted to play g7, but there I miscalculated the final position and quickly jumped to h4.} 23. Bg7 $1 Bg4 24. h8=Q Rxh8 25. Rxh8 Qe3 {Black threatens a checkmate in 1, but it's not a big problem for White.} 26. Bf8+ Ke6 (26... Kd7 27. Rxd5+ Kc7 (27... Ke6 28. Rd6#) 28. Bd6+ Kb6 (28... Kd7 29. Bxe5+ Ke6 30. Rd6+ Ke7 31. Re8#) 29. Bc5+ $18 {with a free rook.}) 27. f5+ $1 Bxf5 (27... Kd7 28. Rxd5+ Kc7 29. Bd6+ Kb6 30. Bc5+ $18 {again White wins the queen.}) 28. Bxf5+ Kxf5 29. Rd3 $16 {White pushes the black queen far from the white king, and then slowly consolidates his pieces. It's clear that White is better, however, the fight is not over yet. I don't remember exactly what I miscalculated in this line. I probably forgot that the f4-f5 check distracts the black bishop from my knight.}) 23... Nd4 $4 {[%emt 0:04:50] This natural move loses the game because it opens the e-file for the white rooks.} ({The correct way was to attack the c2 weakness.} 23... Qb2 $1 $13 {and position becomes very irrational.} 24. Bg7 Qxc2 25. h8=Q Rxh8 26. Rxh8 Bxf5) 24. Nxd4 {[%emt 0:10:15]} exd4 {[%emt 0:00:07]} 25. Kf2 $1 $18 {[%emt 0:00:22] After this, the game is over. Black has no longer an attack, while his king and the pawns on the d-file are very weak.} d3+ {[%emt 0:04:37]} 26. Be3 {[%emt 0:00:28]} d4 {[%emt 0:00:07]} 27. Bf4 {[%emt 0:02:33][%cal Gh1e1] [#]} Rh8 {[%emt 0:05:52]} ({After} 27... d2 {the shortest way to win would be} 28. Rhe1+ $1 dxe1=Q+ 29. Rxe1+ $18 {and White wins a lot of material.}) 28. Rhe1+ {[%emt 0:01:19]} Kd8 {[%emt 0:00:07]} 29. Rxd3 {[%emt 0:00:12] Black can't save the d4 pawn.} Qc5 {[%emt 0:07:05]} ({The bishop's move does not help to advance the d4 pawn.} 29... Bb5 30. Re6 $1 Qc5 31. Rd6+ Kc8 32. R3xd4 $18) 30. Re4 {[%emt 0:03:31]} Kc8 {[%emt 0:02:35]} 31. Rexd4 {[%emt 0:02:32] White has finally got enough material for the queen - the rook, the bishop, and the pawn.} Bb5 {[%emt 0:00:45]} 32. Rd1 {[%emt 0:01:48]} Qe7 {[%emt 0:01:07]} 33. a4 {[%emt 0:00:44] The white pawn goes to weaken the position of the black king.} Bc6 {[%emt 0:00:40]} 34. a5 {[%emt 0:01:50][%csl Rc6][%cal Ga5a6]} Qg7 {[%emt 0:01:30]} 35. Rd6 {[%emt 0:01:51] a5-a6 is an annoying threat.} a6 {[%emt 0:00:40]} 36. Rxc6+ $5 {[%emt 0:01:35]} ({Objectively, this is not the strongest, but after seeing the idea of the exchange sacrifice, I forgot about my initial idea to move the bishop to b6, which would end the game immediately.} 36. Be3 $1 $18 {[%cal Ge3b6]}) 36... bxc6 {[%emt 0:00:07]} 37. Rb1 {[%emt 0:00:06] [#] This is the position I was so adored by that I forgot about 36.e3. f4 and b1 dominate over the black queen, while g6 and the h-pawn control the black rook.} Qa7+ {[%emt 0:00:41]} 38. Kg3 {[%emt 0:00:58]} Kd7 {[%emt 0:01:18]} 39. Rd1+ {[%emt 0:00:03]} Kc8 {[%emt 0:00:13]} 40. Rb1 {[%emt 0:00:00] The last two moves were made to get extra 30 minutes on the clock.} Kd7 {[%emt 0:00:00]} 41. Rb3 {[%emt 0:00:00] White wants to take the c3 pawn so they don't have to worry about the c2 pawn anymore.} c5 $1 {[%emt 0:00:00] This is a nice trick.} 42. Rb6 $1 {[%emt 0:00:00] Cutting off the king.} ({The idea of the pawn's move was to evacuate the king from the 7th rank.} 42. Rxc3 $2 Kc6 $1 {However, my calculation again wasn't perfect here.} 43. Rb3 Kd5 $1 $13 {I didn't see that the black king could keep moving forward.} (43... Rxh7 $2 {I thought, that a capture was forced.} 44. c4 $1 {White threatens to checkmate in 2 - e8 and b6.} Rg7 45. Rb8 $1 {[#] Here is the position of a nice zugzwang for the black queen, as it can't move to e7 due to b6 followed by xb7. The winning plan is to win the f6 pawn. Black has no a good way to develop own pieces.})) 42... Qa8 {[%emt 0:00:00] Even though the evaluation is equal to about +6, it's not that easy to convert it.} 43. Re6 {[%emt 0:00:00][%cal Ra8e4,Re4c2,Re4e1] I decided to begin with preventing both d5 and e4.} ({White's problem is that it's easy to dominate over the black pieces, but it's hard to checkmate with only one rook and one bishop. That's why I had to focus on finding a way to move my light-squared bishop back to its original position.} 43. Rxf6 $1 Qe4 44. Rd6+ Kc8 {The black king has no a choice.} 45. Rb6 Kd7 {[#] And here the key move is coming.} 46. Bf7 $3 {A threat is d6-c8, e6. White wins the black queen.} Rxh7 47. Rd6+ $1 Kc8 (47... Ke7 48. Re6+ $18) 48. Be6+ $1 Kb7 49. Bd5+ $18) 43... Qb7 {[%emt 0:00:00]} 44. Rd6+ {[%emt 0:00:00]} (44. Rxf6 $18) 44... Kc8 $2 {[%emt 0:00:00] This retreat simplifies my task.} 45. Rb6 {[%emt 0:00:00][%cal Gb6b8]} Rxh7 $8 {[%emt 0:00:00] This is the only move because of b8 threat.} 46. Bxh7 {[%emt 0:00:00]} Qe4 {[%emt 0:00:00]} (46... Qxh7 47. Rb8+ Kd7 48. Rb7+ $18 {loses the queen.}) 47. Bg8 $6 {[%emt 0:00:00] This move does not miss a win, but White could minimize a risk of the perpetual check by destroying the f6 pawn.} (47. Rxf6 $1 Qxc2 48. Rc6+ Kd8 (48... Kb7 49. Rc7+ Ka8 50. f6 {h7 attacks the queen.} Qe2 51. f7 $18 {A checkmate is inevitable.}) 49. Rd6+ Kc8 (49... Ke8 50. Bg6+ Kf8 (50... Ke7 51. f6+ Kf8 52. Rd8#) 51. Rd8+ Kg7 (51... Ke7 52. Bg5#) 52. Be5+ Kh6 53. Rh8+ Kg5 54. Rh5#) 50. Bg8 $1 $18 {Two bishops and a rook easily end the game.}) 47... Qe1+ {[%emt 0:00:00] This is the only way to trouble the white king.} ({Black had no time to capture the c2 pawn.} 47... Qxc2 48. Be6+ Kd8 49. Bd6 Qd3+ 50. Kh2 $18 {The checks are over.}) 48. Kh3 {[%emt 0:00:00]} Qh1+ {[%emt 0:00:49]} 49. Bh2 {[%emt 0:00:29]} Qc1 $1 {[%emt 0:00:05] The black queen connects with the h6 square.} 50. Be6+ {[%emt 0:00:52]} Kd8 $18 {[%emt 0:00:05] And we are back to the game position after move 50. [#]} 51. Bd6 {[%emt 0:01:57] This move does not win the game yet, because Black has a way of giving many checks which would force White to repeat the position before move 51.Bd6.} ({The correct way was quite spectacular.} 51. Rb8+ Ke7 52. Rb7+ Ke8 $8 {This is the only good retreat.} (52... Kd8 $4 53. Bc7+ Ke8 54. Bf7+ $1 Kf8 {Otherwise, 55.f4 wins the queen thanks to a discovered check.} 55. Bd6+ Kg7 56. Bg6+ Kh8 57. Rb8+ Kg7 58. Bf8+ Kg8 59. Bh6#) 53. Rh7 $1 Qxc2 {White can play c4 to threaten to the a6 pawn. This would force black to capture the c2 pawn.} 54. Bf7+ Kd8 55. Bc7+ $1 {A mirror variation to 52...d8 line!} Kc8 56. Be6+ Kb7 57. Bf4+ Kc6 58. Rc7+ Kb5 59. Rb7+ Ka4 (59... Kxa5 60. Bd7 $1 Qd3+ 61. Kh2 $1 $18 {The 62.c7 threat wins the queen.}) 60. Bb3+ Qxb3 61. Rxb3 Kxb3 62. g4 $18 {g4-g5 wins the game.}) 51... Qh6+ $2 {[%emt 0:00:35] Black missed his last chance to stay in the game.} 52. Kg4 {[%emt 0:00:26] The white king runs away from the checks.} Qg5+ {[%emt 0:00:28]} 53. Kf3 {[%emt 0:00:05]} Qh5+ {[%emt 0:00:16]} 54. Ke3 {[%emt 0:00:57]} Qg5+ {[%emt 0:00:12]} 55. Kd3 {[%emt 0:00:16]} Qd2+ {[%emt 0:02:26]} 56. Kc4 {[%emt 0:00:08]} Qe2+ {[%emt 0:00:23]} 57. Kb3 {[%emt 0:00:30]} c4+ {[%emt 0:00:09]} 58. Kb4 {[%emt 0:00:17]} Qxc2 {[%emt 0:00:14]} 59. Rb8# {[%emt 0:00:07] As the winner of three beauty prizes in my carreer, I can share with you the main secret of how to win such contests. The positional sacrifice of the queen always impresses a jury!} 1-0

